-- 
Turkish Stocks Fall to 2-Month Low on Loan Report, Moody’s

-- B y   S e l c u k   G o k o l u k
-- 
2011-05-20T15:13:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-20/turkish-stocks-fall-3rd-day-after-credit-card-limits-report.html
Turkish stocks fell to a two-month
low and bond yields climbed on reports that the government may
place limits on credit-card borrowing and after Moody’s
Investors Service placed Yapi & Kredi Bankasi AS on review for a
possible downgrade. The lira declined.  The  ISE National 100 Index (XU100)  of equities dropped 0.7 percent
to 63,298.58 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Istanbul, for a drop of 2
percent this week. Two-year benchmark bond yields climbed
thirteen basis points, or 0.13 percentage point, to 8.95
percent, the highest closing level since April 1, according to
the RBS Istanbul benchmark bond index.  Turkey  may place limits on credit-card borrowing and other
loans after the June 12 general elections to limit the current-
account deficit, Sabah newspaper reported. Authorities are
considering steps that would tie credit-card borrowing limits to
income levels, and introduce higher transaction charges on bank
loans, the newspaper said, without specifying how it got the
information.  “The news reports on new measures are affecting the market
as this will affect the banks’ profits,” Ata Doganoglu, a
trader at Istanbul-based broker Ekspres Invest, said in e-mailed
comments.  The 200-day moving average is now at 65,395.20, Bloomberg
data show, after breaking the 65,200 level this week.  Investor Sales  “There are a lot of speculators,  hedge funds  and local
investors looking at just technical levels and now they are
adjusting their positions accordingly,” Doganoglu said.  Yapi & Kredi Bankasi AS, the Turkish bank owned by  Italy ’s
 UniCredit SpA (UCG)  and Turkey’s  Koc Holding AS (KCHOL) , fell as much as 6.5
percent to a one-year intraday low of 3.88 liras after Moody’s
said it was reviewing the lender’s local-currency deposit
ratings and long-term national-scale ratings. The stock last
traded down 1.7 percent at 4.08 liras.  Foreign investors reduced their holding of Turkish stock in
the week May 13 by $4.36 billion, the largest sale since the
five business days ended Feb. 25, the central bank data showed.  The lira slid 1.1 percent to 1.5912 per dollar, trimming
its gain for the week to 0.4 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
